162,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDM4ODU5NDI4Nw==","github-url":"https://github.com/DFHack/dfhack/issues/183#issuecomment-388594287"},"message":"To add onto what I said previously, I would like some jobs to be driven by the supply of inputs, rather than the number of outputs. I would like it if cooking jobs stayed active as long as there was a supply of ingredients. I would like bind book jobs to always activate whenever there were written-on quires to bind. I would like milling jobs to always be active whenever there is material to mill. The only way to keep these sorts of jobs active now is to set a really high maximum limit for the output and just expect a lot of job cancellation spam. In this case of milling jobs, it's tricky because I can only set limits on powders in general, and there are many different types of powders with many uses. What I would like is a constraint similar to the output constraints, but that lets you set a minimum number of inputs before activating a job. If there are only input constraints and no output constraints, than Workflow should keep a job active as long as the input constraints are met.","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"e90a87fc4d3f9010ece6ce6c9e2c70cb1f11b564"},"timestamp":1545101162,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdDE2MzU5Njg0MQ=="},"target":"6daef4a60e68d8d597d969f33954d38d143269acd0a88d5f69610dcfd676ba23","message":"To add onto what I said previously, I would like some jobs to be driven by the supply of inputs, rather than the number of outputs. I would like it if cooking jobs stayed active as long as there was a supply of ingredients. I would like bind book jobs to always activate whenever there were written-on quires to bind. I would like milling jobs to always be active whenever there is material to mill. The only way to keep these sorts of jobs active now is to set a really high maximum limit for the output and just expect a lot of job cancellation spam. In this case of milling job